Walnford, New Jersey

Walnford is a populated place, specifically an [unincorporated community](/Local_government_in_New_Jersey), nestled along the banks of [Crosswicks Creek](/Crosswicks_Creek). It resides within the boundaries of [Upper Freehold Township](/Upper_Freehold_Township,_New_Jersey), a part of [Monmouth County](/Monmouth_County,_New_Jersey), situated in the [U.S. state](/U.S._state) of [New Jersey](/New_Jersey). The origins of its name trace back to Richard Waln, who was the original proprietor of the land that now constitutes the settlement.

### Geography and Location

The geographical coordinates for Walnford are 40°08′04″N 74°33′36″W / 40.13444°N 74.56000°W. This places it firmly within the United States, specifically in the state of New Jersey, within Monmouth County. Administratively, it falls under Upper Freehold Township. The elevation of Walnford is approximately 46 feet (14 meters) above sea level. It observes the [Eastern Time Zone](/Eastern_Time_Zone) (EST), which is [UTC−05:00](/UTC%E2%88%9205:00), and observes [Daylight Saving Time](/Daylight_saving_time) (EDT), shifting to [UTC−04:00](/UTC%E2%88%9204:00) during the warmer months. The [Geographic Names Information System](/Geographic_Names_Information_System) (GNIS) designates it with the feature ID 881507.

### Historical Significance and Naming

The history of Walnford is intrinsically linked to Richard Waln, a merchant hailing from [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia). In the year 1772, Waln acquired several mills in the vicinity, subsequently bestowing upon the area the name Walnford. His presence was further cemented by the construction of a two-and-a-half-story residence in 1773, a structure that still stands as a testament to that era. This property then passed into the hands of his son, Nicolas Waln, and the Waln family lineage continued to maintain a connection to this place for close to two centuries.

### Historic Walnford and its Preservation

The area known as Historic Walnford functions as an [open-air museum](/Open-air_museum), meticulously maintained and operated by the [Monmouth County Park System](/Monmouth_County_Park_System). This preserved site is an integral part of [Crosswicks Creek Park](/Crosswicks_Creek_Park), offering a glimpse into the past for visitors.

### The Walnford Historic District

Designated as a [U.S. historic place](/Historic_places_in_the_United_States), the Walnford Historic District is a significant enclave spanning approximately 50 acres (20 hectares). This district encompasses the community that developed along Walnford-Davis Station Road and Hill Road. Its inclusion on the [National Register of Historic Places](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) on June 29, 1976, was in recognition of its crucial role in the region's agricultural and commercial development. The district boasts 16 [contributing buildings](/Contributing_buildings) and one contributing structure, notably including the original Waln House, erected in 1773, and the historic grist mill situated on [Crosswicks Creek](/Crosswicks_Creek). The district was also added to the [New Jersey Register of Historic Places](/New_Jersey_Register_of_Historic_Places) on May 8, 1975, under reference number 2070. The architectural style predominantly represented within the district is [Georgian](/Georgian_architecture).

### Architectural Style and Contributing Elements

The Walnford Historic District is characterized by its [Georgian](/Georgian_architecture) architectural style, reflecting the period of its initial development. The district comprises 16 buildings and one structure that are considered to contribute to its historical integrity. Among these are the Waln House, built in 1773 by Richard Waln, and the grist mill that harnessed the power of [Crosswicks Creek](/Crosswicks_Creek). These elements collectively narrate the story of Walnford's past as a center of both agrarian activity and local commerce.

